s to take aim at record labels</a> and share her past experience as a struggling new artist.</p><p> Before then, &#39;Good Luck, Babe!&#39; <a href="https://www.nme.com/lists/end-of-year/best-songs-2024-3817596">was named as <em>NME</em> ’s best song of 2024</a> . “With &#39;Good Luck, Babe!&#39;, Roan set out to write a &#39;big anthemic pop song&#39;. It was an unqualified success: over subtly insistent synth-pop, Roan serves up home truths to someone desperately trying to deny their queerness,” the entry read.</p><p> Her breakthrough debut album <a href="https://www.nme.com/reviews/album/chappell-roan-the-rise-and-fall-of-a-midwest-princess-review-debut-album-radar-3499595">&#39;The Rise And Fall Of A Midwest Princess&#39; was also given a glowing four-star review from <em>NME</em></a> , which described it as “cinematic and swooning”. “&#39;The Rise And Fall Of A Midwest Princess&#39; is a display of Roan&#39;s bold and brazen pen, where she places searing revelations alongside some deliciously cheeky choruses,” it read.</p><p> The post <a href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/chappell-roan-teases-new-song-the-giver-by-sharing-hotline-number-with-fans-3838983">Chappell Roan teases new song &#39;The Giver&#39; by sharing hotline number with fans</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.nme.com">NME</a> .</p> ;
